Goal:
Exercise one Tensor Reduce (fget operation).

Details:
The test only runs in thread 0 of each minion. The test does one single tensor reduce with the FGET operation with the tree depth fixed to 0. In a Neigh build, the pairing will be the following:
   - H0  <- H2
   - H4  <- H6
   - H8  <- H10
   - H12 <- H14

If the 'SELF_CHECK' variable is set, each tensor reduce operation is self-checked following these steps:
   0) Declare a shared Global Array Variable with size equal or bigger than the number Minions in the SoC
   1) Tensor Wait to make sure the previous operation is done
   2) Dump the whole VPU RF content into the global shared memory region (pre-vpurf)
   3) Do an FCC synchronization to make sure everyone has finished any operation of the previous loop iteration 
   4) Execute the Tensor Reduce Auto operation
   5) Tensor Wait to make sure the current operation is done and self-check the tensor error value (should be 0).
   6) Model the Tensor Reduce Auto behaviour using RISC-V basic instructions.
        - This model will compute the Sender and the Receiver Minion ID.
        - If the self-check code is executed by the Sender Minion, dump the VPUR RF content in a memory position in the stack (post-vpurf). Make sure pre-vpurf contains the same as post-vpurf.
        - If the self-check code is executed by the Receiver Minion: 
           · Dump out the VPU RF content into a local memory region in the stack (post-vpurf).
           · It will read the global shared memory of the sender minion VPU RF content (dumped by the sender minion in step 2)
           · It will read the global shared memory of the receiver minion VPU RF content (dumped by the receiver minion in step 2)
           · Using RISC-V basic instructions it will model the configured reduce operation.
           · The reduce result is stored in a local variable in the stack (scratch).
           · The content from post-vpurf and scratch is compared and must be identical.
